WEEK 11 – Working on Windows 11 (Ngrok + Jenkins + GitHub Webhook)

Step 1: Disable Antivirus 1. Go to Settings 2. Privacy & Security 3.
Windows Security 4. Turn OFF antivirus temporarily.

Step 2: Sign Up on Ngrok 1. Visit https://ngrok.com 2. Sign Up with
name, email, password (10+ characters) 3. Log in.

Step 3: Download Ngrok 1. Click Download for Windows (64-bit) 2. Save
the zip file.

Step 4: Install and Open Ngrok 1. Extract zip file 2. Run ngrok.exe
Ngrok command prompt appears as below

Step 5: Connect Ngrok Account 1. Copy Authtoken from Ngrok dashboard->inn your Authroken 2.
Run: ngrok config add-authtoken

1.open cmd at ngrok:ngrok config add-authtoken 34ejJvRYKqtjvBUEYEnxudIbpb7_33i6pYx8BJ2cZ1TpwasWq
 2. Run: ngrok http 8081 3. Copy the https ngrok
URL generated.(at forwarding)

Step 7: Create Webhook in GitHub 1. Repo → Settings → Webhooks → Add
Webhook
2. Payload URL: 	Add url https://unhired-stormily-alaine.ngrok-free.dev/github-webhook/
3. Content Type: application/json 
4. Select “Just the push event” ,active 5. Add Webhook.

Step 8: Configure Jenkins for Webhooks 1. Open Jenkins Dashboard(Maven_java_build) 2.
Select Job → Configure 3. Build Triggers: ✔ GitHub hook trigger for
GITScm polling 4. Save.

Step 9: Test the Setup 1. Make code change → push to GitHub 2. GitHub
triggers webhook 3. Jenkins auto-build starts.eg:hello webhook to webhook
 open jenkins run build pipeline
Outcome: GitHub and Jenkins connected successfully using Ngrok +
Webhooks.
